10","1453":"1453","1288":"1288","1284":"1284","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","England":"England","Plymouth, Devon, England":"Plymouth, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Forbes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Forbes in Tullynessle, Aberdeenshire, so named from Gaelic <i>forba</i> ‘field, district’ + the locative suffix <i>-ais</i>. The placename is pronounced in two syllables, with the stress on the second, and the surname until recently reflected this. Today, however, it is generally a monosyllable.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Firbhisigh</b> ‘son of <i>Fearbhisigh</i>’, a personal name composed of elements meaning ‘man’ + ‘prosperity’.","History: A family of this name (see 2 above) in Connacht was famous for its traditional historians, compilers of the Book of Lecan."],"variants":[{"name":"Fawbush","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which ispronounced as two syllables in Aberdeenshire. Compare   Forbush  ."]},{"name":"Forbus","meanings":["Altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , reflecting thetraditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Forbush","meanings":["Scottish: altered form of   Forbes  , which was traditionally pronounced as two syllables. This surname is now rare in Britain.","Altered form of German <b>Vorbusch</b>, a topographic name for someone living on the edge of a wood, from <i>vor</i> ‘in front of’ + North German <i>Busch</i> ‘wood, bush’."]},{"name":"Fobbs","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Furbush","meanings":["Probably an altered form of Scottish   Forbes  , which is traditionally pronounced as two syllables. Compare   Furbish  ."]},{"name":"Forbis","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]},{"name":"Fobes","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  ."]},{"name":"Forbess","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Forbes  , reflecting the traditional pronunciation as two syllables."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay"